#!/usr/bin/env -S uv run --script
# /// script
# requires-python = ">=3.11"
# dependencies = [
#     "httpx>=0.27",
# ]
# ///
"""
clickup — agent-first CLI for ClickUp spaces, lists & tasks.

This tool is designed to be invoked by agents. Run `clickup help` to load
the full usage contract on demand — do not rely on memorised knowledge of
its surface.

CONNECTIONS
  Configuration resolves as named connections. With no registry the sole
  connection is `default`: CLICKUP_API_TOKEN (a ClickUp personal API token,
  `pk_…`) resolved through the standard cascade — a project .env(.local),
  then ~/.config/clickup/credentials.env, then the process env. Never pass
  the token on the command line.

  A project that acts as several ClickUp identities declares them in
  <project>/.capabilities/clickup/connections.json:
    {
      "default": "<id>",
      "connections": {
        "<id>": {
          "secret_env": "CLICKUP_<ID>_TOKEN",
          "allow_write": true,
          "workspace_id": "123",
          "external_id_field": "external_id"
        }
      }
    }
  The registry resolves project envelope first, else the machine-level
  ~/.config/clickup/connections.json; first found wins, never merged.

  The entry names the env var holding its token ("secret_env"); the value
  resolves through the cascade above. "allow_write": false makes the
  connection read-only: every mutating verb exits 4, and no flag lifts the
  gate. Writes default to allowed (a workspace the consumer owns). Optional
  non-secret settings can live on the entry too: "workspace_id" is the default
  workspace/team for dedup queries; "external_id_field" (alias "external_id")
  is the custom field UUID or field name used as the settable external-id key.

  Selection: --connection <id> (accepted anywhere on the command line).
  Unflagged, the registry's "default" pointer applies, else the sole entry;
  several entries without a pointer is refused as ambiguous.

Global option (accepted after any subcommand):
  --token-env <KEY>   Act as a different identity by naming the env/cred KEY
                      that holds the token (default CLICKUP_API_TOKEN; with a
                      registry connection it overrides that entry's secret_env).
                      The value never touches the command line — only the key
                      name. Drop the alternate token in the env/credentials
                      (e.g. CLICKUP_ALT_TOKEN=…) and pass
                      --token-env CLICKUP_ALT_TOKEN. It never lifts a
                      connection's write gate.

  CLICKUP_WORKSPACE_ID and CLICKUP_EXTERNAL_ID_FIELD (alias CLICKUP_EXTERNAL_ID)
  can also be set through the same cascade (project .env/.env.local,
  ~/.config/clickup/credentials.env, process env). Connection entry values win
  over env files. The external-id field may be a UUID or a field name resolvable
  from the target list.

THE HIERARCHY
  ClickUp nests Workspace (the API calls it a "team") > Space > Folder > List
  > Task > Subtask. A List is the task container (the Asana "project" analog);
  board columns are STATUSES set on the task (there is no section object);
  tags are space-scoped and addressed by name.

Commands:
  clickup help                                Print this document.
  clickup connections                         Where every connection's values
                                              resolve from (tier, source,
                                              secrets masked). Local only.
  clickup doctor [--connection <id>]          Health check — resolve token,
                                              confirm identity, list
                                              workspaces — every connection,
                                              or one.

Contract commands (the same on every capability):
  clickup stub                                One-line awareness text.
  clickup manifest --json                     Machine-readable declaration.
  clickup guide [<topic>]                     Guide topics / one guide body,
                                              fetched live from the docs base.
  clickup ids list|get <l>|set <l> <v>|rm <l> The project identifiers envelope
        [--note <text>]                       (.capabilities/clickup/identifiers.json).
  clickup refs                                Menu of the project's reference
                                              files for this capability.

Read:
  clickup whoami                              Confirm token + identity.
  clickup workspaces                          List workspaces (teams) the token sees.
  clickup members [--workspace ID]            List a workspace's members (id +
                                              username + email). Defaults to the
                                              sole workspace when only one exists.
  clickup spaces --workspace ID               List spaces in a workspace.
  clickup folders --space ID                  List folders in a space.
  clickup lists [--folder ID] [--space ID]    List lists. --folder lists a
                                              folder's lists; --space lists the
                                              folderless lists directly under a
                                              space (they appear ONLY here).
  clickup statuses --list ID                  List a list's statuses — the board
                                              columns, each with its type
                                              (open|custom|done|closed). The
                                              "what columns exist?" read; moving
                                              a task between columns is `update --status`.
  clickup tags --space ID                     List a space's tags (name + colours).
  clickup fields --list ID                    List a list's custom fields (id +
                                              name + type) — resolve a field's
                                              UUID before `field-set`.
  clickup tasks --list ID [--all] [--archived]   List tasks in a list. Incomplete
        [--subtasks] [--status NAME ...]      only unless --all (closed statuses
        [--limit N] [--page N]                included). --status filters to named
                                              statuses (repeatable). --subtasks
                                              includes subtasks. Paginates to
                                              --limit (default 100); --page reads
                                              a single 0-indexed page of 100.
  clickup task <task> [--with-subtasks]       Show one task in full (status,
        [--custom-id --workspace ID]          assignees, tags, custom_fields,
                                              dependencies, linked_tasks, url).
                                              --with-subtasks attaches its
                                              subtasks. --custom-id resolves
                                              <task> as a Custom Task ID (needs
                                              --workspace).
  clickup task-context <task> [--json]        One call → the task plus everything
                                              adjacent: description (markdown),
                                              comment thread, attachment
                                              pointers, dependencies one level
                                              deep (each with its own description,
                                              thread, attachments), dependents as
                                              state lines. Emits a prompt-ready
                                              markdown envelope stamped with its
                                              assembly time (UTC); --json emits
                                              the same tree structured.
  clickup comments <task> [--limit N]         List a task's comments (text +
                                              date + author), the N most recent
                                              in chronological order.
  clickup subtasks <task>                     List a task's subtasks.
  clickup deps <task> [--dependents]          List what <task> waits on (or, with
                                              --dependents, what waits on it).
  clickup attachments <task>                  List a task's attachments (id +
                                              title + url; read from the task).
  clickup find [--workspace ID] [--list ID]   Resolve a task by a dedup key —
        --field UUID --value V                task JSON on a hit, null + exit 0 on
        | --external-id V [--field FIELD]     a miss. --external-id uses the
                                             configured external_id custom field
                                             (or --field override, UUID/name);
                                             --list resolves field names.
        | <custom-task-id>                     a miss. Two modes: --field/--value
                                              matches a custom field workspace-wide
                                              (the SETTABLE external-ID key — set it
                                              with `create --external-id`,
                                              `create --field`, or `field-set`);
                                              a bare <custom-task-id> is the ClickApp
                                              Custom Task ID lookup (read-only —
                                              ClickUp assigns those, the API cannot
                                              set them). Use --field for dedup.
  clickup field-get <task> [<field>]          Read a task's custom field values —
                                              all, or one addressed by UUID or name.
  clickup assigned --workspace ID             The "what's waiting on my input, and
        [--assignee ID] [--all]               for how long?" read: tasks assigned
        [--status NAME ...] [--limit N]       to you (or --assignee), incomplete
                                              unless --all, stalest first — each with
                                              its last-touch timestamp and idle age.

Write:
  clickup create --list ID --name NAME        Create a task in a list.
        [--desc TEXT|-] [--markdown TEXT|-]    --markdown (default) stores a
        [--assignee ID ...] [--status NAME]   markdown body (ClickUp renders it);
        [--tag NAME ...] [--priority N]        --desc stores literal plain text.
        [--due-on YYYY-MM-DD]                  Pass at most one. '-' reads stdin.
        [--due-at ISO8601] [--parent ID]      --assignee repeatable (user id).
        [--external-id V] [--workspace ID]     --external-id enforces a best-effort
                                              dedup preflight against the configured
                                              external_id custom field, then stamps
                                              that field during creation. Requires
                                              --workspace unless CLICKUP_WORKSPACE_ID
                                              or connection workspace_id is set.
        [--field UUID=VALUE ...]              --priority 1=Urgent 2=High 3=Normal
                                              4=Low. --due-on is all-day; --due-at
                                              carries time-of-day; not both.
                                              --parent makes it a SUBTASK (parent
                                              must be in the same list). --field
                                              sets a custom field at creation
                                              (repeatable) — stamp an external-ID
                                              key here, then `find --field` it.
  clickup update <task> [--name N]            Update fields on a task. --markdown/
        [--desc T|-] [--markdown T|-]          --desc as for create. --status moves
        [--status NAME] [--priority N]         the column. --add-assignee /
        [--due-on D] [--due-at ISO]            --rem-assignee add or remove
        [--add-assignee ID ...]                assignees (ClickUp updates use an
        [--rem-assignee ID ...] [--archive]    add/remove set, not a replace).
                                              --archive archives the task.
  clickup comment <task> [--text TEXT|-]      Add a comment to a task. --assignee
        [--assignee ID] [--notify-all]        assigns + notifies that user;
                                              --notify-all notifies everyone on
                                              the task. (ClickUp comments are
                                              plain text — no @mention segment.)
  clickup complete <task> [--reopen]          Mark a task complete by setting its
        [--force] [--no-rollup]               list's closed status (--reopen sets
                                              the first open status). REFUSES
                                              (exit 7) if the task has incomplete
                                              dependencies — pass --force to
                                              override. On success it cascades:
                                              auto-completes any parent whose
                                              subtasks are now all done, and
                                              reports dependents this unblocked.
                                              --no-rollup skips the cascade.
                                              (To move a task to an arbitrary
                                              column, use `update --status`.)
  clickup assign <task> [--add ID ...]        Add and/or remove assignees on a
        [--rem ID ...]                        task. <ID> is a user id.
  clickup watch <task> [--add ID ...]         Add and/or remove watchers — the
        [--rem ID ...]                        follower analog; a watcher is
                                              notified of the task's activity.
  clickup tag-create --space ID --name NAME   Create a tag in a space.
        [--fg HEX] [--bg HEX]
  clickup tag-add <task> <tag>                Add a tag to a task. <tag> is a
                                              tag NAME (tags are name-addressed).
  clickup tag-remove <task> <tag>             Remove a tag from a task.
  clickup dep-add <task> --on ID [--on ...]   Mark <task> as depending on each
                                              --on task (waits on them).
  clickup dep-remove <task> --on ID [...]     Remove dependency links from <task>.
  clickup field-set <task> <field> --value V  Set a custom field on a task.
        [--json]                              <field> is the field UUID (`fields`
                                              lists them). --value is the literal
                                              value; --json parses it as JSON
                                              first (for typed/relationship fields).
  clickup field-clear <task> <field>          Clear a custom field on a task.
  clickup deliverable --list ID               Create a PAIRED request + dependent:
        --request-name N --agent-name N        a request task assigned to
        --supervisor USER --agent USER         --supervisor (the human whose input
        [--request-markdown T|-]               is needed) and an agent task assigned
        [--agent-markdown T|-]                 to --agent that DEPENDS ON it, so
        [--status NAME] [--parent ID]          completing the request unblocks the
        [--state-field UUID]                   agent task. --state-field stamps
                                              {phase,last_touch} JSON into a (UI-
                                              created) custom field on both tasks.
                                              Not idempotent — ClickUp has no
                                              settable dedup key.
  clickup task-delete <task> --yes            Delete a task. IRREVERSIBLE — refuses
        [--custom-id --workspace ID]           without --yes (the gate; confirm with
                                              the human first).
  clickup attach <task> FILE [--name NAME]    Upload a local FILE to a task
                                              (multipart). --name overrides the
                                              display name. (File upload only —
                                              ClickUp has no attach-by-URL.)
  clickup list-create --name NAME             Create a list. --folder makes it a
        [--folder ID] [--space ID]            folder list; --space makes it a
        [--content TEXT]                      folderless list under the space.
  clickup webhooks --workspace ID             List a workspace's webhooks.
  clickup webhook-create --workspace ID       Register a webhook delivering to the
        --endpoint URL [--event E ...]        HTTPS endpoint. --event is repeatable
        [--space ID] [--folder ID]            (e.g. taskCreated taskStatusUpdated
        [--list ID] [--task ID]               taskCommentPosted); omit for all
                                              events. The scope flags narrow it to
                                              one space/folder/list/task. The
                                              response carries the signing secret
                                              once — capture it. (No handshake.)
  clickup webhook-delete <webhook> --yes      Delete a webhook (stops deliveries).
                                              IRREVERSIBLE — refuses without --yes
                                              (the gate; confirm with the human first).

References:
  <task> accepts a bare task id OR a full ClickUp URL (the id after /t/ is
  extracted). User ids and the like are bare numeric ids.

Input:
  `comment --text`, `create/update --desc|--markdown` accept inline text, a
  file path, or "-" for stdin (one '-' per command). List/space/folder/team
  ids that are stable for a repo belong in that repo's own reference file, not
  here, or in `clickup ids`.

I/O contract:
  - Success: JSON on stdout, exit 0.
  - Error:   {"error": {"code", "message", "hint", "status"}} on stderr,
             non-zero exit.

Exit codes:
  0  success
  2  auth (unauthorized / forbidden / missing credentials)
  3  not found
  4  policy refusal — the project gate (.capabilities/settings.json) on any
     verb, or a write verb on a read-only connection (allow_write: false).
     Ask the user; never lift a gate yourself.
  5  server / network (5xx, timeout, rate-limit exhausted)
  6  input / validation
  7  blocked (task has incomplete dependencies; see `complete`)

Notes:
  - Dates are epoch milliseconds on the wire; pass --due-on (all-day) or
    --due-at (ISO8601, time-of-day) and the CLI converts.
  - Completion is status-based: a task is "done" when its status type is
    `done` or `closed`. `complete` discovers the list's closed status and sets
    it; there is no boolean done flag.
  - Board columns ARE statuses (no section object) — `statuses` lists them,
    `update --status` moves a task. Statuses are UI-only: the API cannot create,
    edit, or delete a status, so there is no status-management surface here.
  - Custom field DEFINITIONS are UI-only too: the API reads them (`fields`,
    `field-get`) and reads/writes their VALUES (`field-set`, `field-clear`) but
    cannot create, retype, or delete the field itself. Provision a field once in
    the UI, then drive its value from here (e.g. a machine-state field for
    `deliverable --state-field`).
  - External-ID / dedup parity: ClickUp Custom Task IDs are read-only via the
    API, so the settable dedup key is a (UI-created) text custom field. Stamp it
    at creation with `create --external-id <key>` after configuring
    CLICKUP_EXTERNAL_ID_FIELD (or connection external_id_field), and resolve it
    with `find --external-id <key>`. This is a best-effort create preflight, not
    server-side uniqueness; concurrent producers can still race.
  - Tags are space-scoped and addressed by name (no tag ids).
  - Custom Task IDs are assigned by ClickUp's ClickApp and are read-only via
    the API: `find`/`task --custom-id` resolve by them, nothing sets them.
  - Rate limit is per token (100 req/min on most plans); a 429 is absorbed by
    waiting for the reset, then retried.
  - Listing paginates to --limit (default 100). Raise --limit or filter by
    --status to read more.
"""

import argparse
import json
import os
import re
import sys
import time
from datetime import datetime, timezone
from pathlib import Path
from typing import NoReturn

import httpx

API_BASE = "https://api.clickup.com/api/v2"
TIMEOUT = httpx.Timeout(30.0)
MAX_RETRIES = 3

# --- Capability declaration (protocol 2) — one home for every contract fact --

NAME = "clickup"
PROTOCOL = 2
SUMMARY = ("ClickUp CLI over the REST API — read/create/update/comment-on tasks and "
           "subtasks, complete via status, manage assignees, tags, dependencies, "
           "custom fields, attachments, and webhooks across spaces and lists.")
SCOPE = "project"   # credential scope: "project" | "user"
CRED_KEYS = [
    {"key": "CLICKUP_API_TOKEN", "secret": True, "required": True,
     "note": "personal API token (pk_…; default identity, alternates via --token-env)"},
]
WRITE_VERBS = {     # domain verbs that mutate ClickUp
    "create", "update", "comment", "complete", "assign", "watch",
    "tag-create", "tag-add", "tag-remove", "dep-add", "dep-remove",
    "field-set", "field-clear", "attach", "list-create", "deliverable",
    "task-delete", "webhook-create", "webhook-delete",
}
WRITE_DEFAULT = True    # writes stay inside a workspace the consumer owns
DOCS_BASE = ""      # upstream guides base URL; "" while no guides ship
TOPICS: list = []   # shipped guide topics
STATE = False       # True when the capability writes session/cache state
POST_INSTALL: list = []

_CONFIG_HOME = Path(os.environ.get("XDG_CONFIG_HOME") or (Path.home() / ".config"))
CONFIG_DIR = _CONFIG_HOME / "clickup"
CREDENTIALS_ENV = CONFIG_DIR / "credentials.env"
_STATE_HOME = Path(os.environ.get("XDG_STATE_HOME") or (Path.home() / ".local" / "state"))


# >>> contract: capability core (generated — edit contract/preamble.py, run `capabilities sync-contract`) >>>

# --- Error reporting ---------------------------------------------------------

def _die(exit_code: int, code: str, message: str,
         hint: str | None = None, status: int | None = None) -> NoReturn:
    err: dict = {"code": code, "message": message}
    if hint:
        err["hint"] = hint
    if status is not None:
        err["status"] = status
    sys.stderr.write(json.dumps({"error": err}, ensure_ascii=False) + "\n")
    sys.exit(exit_code)


def _emit(value) -> None:
    if isinstance(value, str):
        sys.stdout.write(value)
        if value and not value.endswith("\n"):
            sys.stdout.write("\n")
    else:
        sys.stdout.write(json.dumps(value, ensure_ascii=False, indent=2) + "\n")


# --- Project / file plumbing -------------------------------------------------

def _parse_env_file(path: Path) -> dict:
    """Parse a KEY=VALUE env/dotenv file. Missing/unreadable file -> {}."""
    out: dict = {}
    try:
        text = path.read_text()
    except OSError:
        return out
    for line in text.splitlines():
        line = line.strip()
        if not line or line.startswith("#") or "=" not in line:
            continue
        k, v = line.split("=", 1)
        k = k.strip()
        if k.startswith("export "):
            k = k[len("export "):].strip()
        out[k] = v.strip().strip('"').strip("'")
    return out


def _project_root() -> Path | None:
    """Nearest project root, walking up from $CLAUDE_PROJECT_DIR (else cwd):
    the first directory holding .capabilities/, .env(.local), or .git.
    $HOME is never a project root (the machine registry lives there)."""
    start = os.environ.get("CLAUDE_PROJECT_DIR") or os.getcwd()
    here = Path(start).resolve()
    home = Path.home().resolve()
    for d in (here, *here.parents):
        if d == home:
            return None
        if ((d / ".capabilities").is_dir() or (d / ".env").exists()
                or (d / ".env.local").exists() or (d / ".git").is_dir()):
            return d
    return None


def _project_env() -> dict:
    """Project .env(.local) at the project root. .env.local overrides .env."""
    root = _project_root()
    if root is None:
        return {}
    merged = _parse_env_file(root / ".env")
    merged.update(_parse_env_file(root / ".env.local"))  # .local wins
    return merged


def _gate() -> None:
    """absent → run; enabled → run; disabled → exit 4. Unreadable never blocks."""
    root = _project_root()
    if root is None:
        return
    gate_file = root / ".capabilities" / "settings.json"
    try:
        entry = json.loads(gate_file.read_text()).get("capabilities", {}).get(NAME)
    except (OSError, ValueError):
        return
    if isinstance(entry, dict) and entry.get("enabled") is False:
        _die(4, "disabled",
             f"{NAME} is disabled in this project ({gate_file})",
             "Do not enable it yourself — ask the user whether to enable it, then stop.")


def _env_dir() -> Path | None:
    """The capability's envelope dir in the project: .capabilities/<NAME>/."""
    root = _project_root()
    return (root / ".capabilities" / NAME) if root is not None else None


def _state_dir() -> Path:
    """State follows the scope of the credentials that minted it; project state
    lands inside the envelope only where .capabilities/ already exists."""
    if SCOPE == "project":
        root = _project_root()
        if root is not None and (root / ".capabilities").is_dir():
            return root / ".capabilities" / NAME / "state"
    return _STATE_HOME / NAME


# --- Capability contract (protocol 2) — the declaration surface --------------

def _docs_base() -> str:
    key = f"{NAME.upper()}_DOCS_BASE"
    return (_project_env().get(key)
            or _parse_env_file(CREDENTIALS_ENV).get(key)
            or os.environ.get(key)
            or DOCS_BASE)


def _cmd_guide(argv: list[str]) -> None:
    if not argv:
        _emit(sorted(TOPICS)); return
    topic = argv[0]
    if topic not in TOPICS:
        _die(3, "not_found", f"no guide topic {topic!r}",
             f"topics: {', '.join(sorted(TOPICS)) or 'none shipped'}")
    import httpx as _hx
    url = _docs_base().rstrip("/") + "/" + topic + ".md"
    cache_dir = _STATE_HOME / NAME / "guides"
    cache, etag_f = cache_dir / f"{topic}.md", cache_dir / f"{topic}.etag"
    headers = {}
    if cache.exists() and etag_f.exists():
        headers["If-None-Match"] = etag_f.read_text().strip()
    try:
        resp = _hx.get(url, headers=headers, timeout=10.0, follow_redirects=True)
        if resp.status_code == 200:
            cache_dir.mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)
            cache.write_text(resp.text)
            if resp.headers.get("etag"):
                etag_f.write_text(resp.headers["etag"])
            _emit(resp.text); return
        if resp.status_code == 304 and cache.exists():
            _emit(cache.read_text()); return
        if resp.status_code == 404:
            _die(3, "not_found", f"guide {topic!r} missing upstream", url)
        raise _hx.HTTPError(f"upstream returned {resp.status_code}")
    except _hx.HTTPError as e:
        if cache.exists():
            sys.stderr.write(json.dumps(
                {"warning": f"upstream unreachable; serving cached copy ({e})"},
                ensure_ascii=False) + "\n")
            _emit(cache.read_text()); return
        _die(5, "network_error", f"could not fetch guide {topic!r}; no cache exists", url)


def _cmd_ids(argv: list[str]) -> None:
    sub = argv[0] if argv else "list"
    envdir = _env_dir()
    ids_file = (envdir / "identifiers.json") if envdir else None
    data: dict = {}
    if ids_file and ids_file.exists():
        try:
            data = json.loads(ids_file.read_text())
        except ValueError:
            _die(6, "bad_envelope", f"{ids_file} is not valid JSON")
    if sub == "list":
        _emit(data); return
    if sub == "get":
        if len(argv) < 2 or argv[1] not in data:
            _die(3, "not_found", "unknown identifier label",
                 f"`{NAME} ids list` shows the labels")
        _emit((data[argv[1]] or {}).get("value")); return
    if sub == "set":
        if len(argv) < 3:
            _die(6, "input", f"usage: {NAME} ids set <label> <value> [--note <text>]")
        if envdir is None or not envdir.parent.is_dir():
            _die(6, "no_envelope", "no .capabilities/ envelope in this project",
                 "run `capabilities init` first")
        label, raw = argv[1], argv[2]
        try:
            value = json.loads(raw)
        except ValueError:
            value = raw
        note = ""
        if "--note" in argv:
            ni = argv.index("--note")
            if ni + 1 >= len(argv):
                _die(6, "input", "--note needs a value")
            note = argv[ni + 1]
        data[label] = {"value": value, "note": note or (data.get(label) or {}).get("note", "")}
        envdir.mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)
        ids_file.write_text(json.dumps(data, ensure_ascii=False, indent=2, sort_keys=True) + "\n")
        _emit({"set": label}); return
    if sub == "rm":
        if len(argv) < 2 or argv[1] not in data:
            _die(3, "not_found", "unknown identifier label",
                 f"`{NAME} ids list` shows the labels")
        del data[argv[1]]
        ids_file.write_text(json.dumps(data, ensure_ascii=False, indent=2, sort_keys=True) + "\n")
        _emit({"removed": argv[1]}); return
    _die(6, "input", f"unknown ids subcommand {sub!r}", f"{NAME} ids list|get|set|rm")


def _cmd_refs() -> None:
    envdir = _env_dir()
    refdir = (envdir / "reference") if envdir else None
    out = []
    if refdir and refdir.is_dir():
        for md in sorted(refdir.glob("*.md")):
            name = desc = None
            try:
                lines = md.read_text().splitlines()
            except OSError:
                continue
            if lines and lines[0].strip() == "---":
                for line in lines[1:30]:
                    if line.strip() == "---":
                        break
                    if line.startswith("name:"):
                        name = line.split(":", 1)[1].strip()
                    elif line.startswith("description:"):
                        desc = line.split(":", 1)[1].strip()
            if name:
                out.append({"name": name, "description": desc or "", "path": str(md)})
    _emit(out)


def _contract(argv: list[str]) -> None:
    """Dispatch the contract verbs; domain verbs fall through to the CLI's own
    parser. Runs after _gate(), before any credential is resolved."""
    cmd = argv[0] if argv else ""
    if cmd == "stub":
        _emit(f"{SUMMARY} Run `{NAME} help`.")
    elif cmd == "manifest":
        _emit({"name": NAME, "protocol": PROTOCOL, "summary": SUMMARY,
               "credentials": {"scope": SCOPE, "keys": CRED_KEYS},
               "docs": {"base": DOCS_BASE, "topics": sorted(TOPICS)},
               "state": STATE, "post_install": POST_INSTALL})
    elif cmd == "guide":
        _cmd_guide(argv[1:])
    elif cmd == "ids":
        _cmd_ids(argv[1:])
    elif cmd == "refs":
        _cmd_refs()
    elif cmd == "connections":
        _cmd_connections()
    else:
        return
    sys.exit(0)

# <<< contract: capability core <<<


# --- Credentials -------------------------------------------------------------

def _load_token(key: str = "CLICKUP_API_TOKEN") -> str:
    """Resolve a ClickUp token by env-var NAME through the credential cascade — a
    project .env(.local), then ~/.config/clickup/credentials.env, then the process
    env; first non-empty wins. `key` defaults to CLICKUP_API_TOKEN; the global
    `--token-env <KEY>` flag selects an alternate key to act as another identity.
    The token value never travels on the command line — only its name."""
    tok = (_project_env().get(key)
           or _parse_env_file(CREDENTIALS_ENV).get(key)
           or os.environ.get(key)
           or "").strip()
    if tok:
        return tok
    if key == "CLICKUP_API_TOKEN":
        _die(2, "missing_token",
             f"CLICKUP_API_TOKEN not found in a project .env, {CREDENTIALS_ENV}, or the environment",
             "add CLICKUP_API_TOKEN=<your pk_ token> to the user config or a project .env")
    _die(2, "missing_token",
         f"{key} not found in a project .env, {CREDENTIALS_ENV}, or the environment",
         f"add {key}=<token> to the user config or a project .env to use --token-env {key}")


# >>> contract: connections (generated — edit contract/preamble.py, run `capabilities sync-contract`) >>>

def _resolve_env_key(key: str) -> tuple[str | None, str | None, Path | None]:
    """Resolve one env key through cascade tiers 2-4: project .env(.local) →
    user credentials.env → process env. Returns (value, tier, source)."""
    root = _project_root()
    if root is not None:
        for fname in (".env.local", ".env"):
            val = _parse_env_file(root / fname).get(key)
            if val:
                return val, "project", root / fname
    val = _parse_env_file(CREDENTIALS_ENV).get(key)
    if val:
        return val, "user", CREDENTIALS_ENV
    val = os.environ.get(key)
    if val:
        return val, "env", None
    return None, None, None


def _mask(value: str) -> str:
    return ("…" + value[-4:]) if len(value) >= 8 else "****"


def _connections_registry() -> tuple[dict | None, Path | None]:
    """The connections envelope and its path: project envelope first, else the
    user config home. First found wins, never merged; (None, None) when neither
    declares one (the implicit default connection applies)."""
    envdir = _env_dir()
    candidates = ([envdir / "connections.json"] if envdir else []) + \
                 [_CONFIG_HOME / NAME / "connections.json"]
    for reg_file in candidates:
        if not reg_file.is_file():
            continue
        try:
            raw = json.loads(reg_file.read_text())
        except (ValueError, OSError) as e:
            _die(6, "bad_config", f"cannot read {reg_file}: {e}")
        if not isinstance(raw, dict) or not isinstance(raw.get("connections"), dict) \
                or not raw["connections"]:
            _die(6, "bad_config", f"{reg_file} is not a connections envelope",
                 'expected {"default": "<id>", "connections": { ... }}')
        return raw, reg_file
    return None, None


def _select_connection(reg: dict | None, wanted: str | None) -> tuple[str, dict | None]:
    """flag → default pointer → sole entry → die 6. No registry → the implicit
    default. A connection's own `address` field selects it too (used where a
    connection carries a human-recognizable address; absent fields never match)."""
    if reg is None:
        if wanted and wanted != "default":
            _die(6, "unknown_connection",
                 "no connections registry; the sole connection is 'default'",
                 "the implicit default resolves from the credential cascade")
        return "default", None
    conns = reg["connections"]
    if wanted:
        if wanted in conns:
            return wanted, conns[wanted]
        for cid, entry in conns.items():
            if (entry or {}).get("address", "").lower() == wanted.lower():
                return cid, entry
        _die(6, "unknown_connection", f"no connection matches {wanted!r}",
             f"known: {', '.join(conns)}")
    default = reg.get("default")
    if default:
        if default not in conns:
            _die(6, "bad_default", f"default points to unknown connection {default!r}",
                 f"known: {', '.join(conns)}")
        return default, conns[default]
    if len(conns) == 1:
        cid = next(iter(conns))
        return cid, conns[cid]
    _die(6, "ambiguous_connection",
         f"registry defines {len(conns)} connections and no default; "
         f"pass --connection <id>",
         f"known: {', '.join(conns)}")


def _write_gate(conn_id: str, allow_write: bool, verb: str) -> None:
    """Policy from the committed registry; nothing in the cascade lifts it."""
    if verb in WRITE_VERBS and not allow_write:
        _die(4, "read_only",
             f"connection {conn_id!r} does not allow writes",
             "Do not lift the gate yourself — ask the user; granting is "
             "`allow_write: true` on this connection in connections.json.")


def _key_report(key: str, secret: bool, required: bool,
                value: str | None, tier: str | None, source) -> dict:
    return {"key": key, "secret": secret, "required": required,
            "set": bool(value), "tier": tier if value else None,
            "source": str(source) if (value and source) else None,
            "value": (_mask(value) if secret else value) if value else None}


def _missing_required(keys: list) -> list:
    """Required report rows (from _key_report) that did not resolve through the
    cascade — empty ⇒ credentials present. The primitive behind doctor's
    network-free readiness gate, read from the same per-key resolution
    `connections` reports, so the gate and the report can never disagree."""
    return [k["key"] for k in keys if k["required"] and not k["set"]]


def _doctor_gate(report: dict, wanted: str | None) -> None:
    """doctor's network-free readiness gate. Refuse with exit 2 — naming the
    unresolved required keys, before any round-trip — when a connection under
    test cannot resolve its required config through the cascade, so readiness is
    judged by the same resolution `connections` reports, never a parallel check.
    Checks the selected connection, else every connection in the report."""
    conns = report.get("connections") or {}
    targets = [wanted] if (wanted and wanted in conns) else list(conns)
    problems: dict = {}
    for cid in targets:
        miss = _missing_required((conns.get(cid) or {}).get("keys") or [])
        if miss:
            problems[cid] = miss
    if problems:
        detail = "; ".join(f"{c}: {', '.join(ks)}" for c, ks in sorted(problems.items()))
        _die(2, "credentials_missing",
             f"unresolved required config — {detail}",
             f"set each in the project .env/.env.local, the user credentials.env, "
             f"or process env; `{NAME} connections` shows where every value resolves")

# <<< contract: connections <<<


# --- Connections ---------------------------------------------------------------

def _connections_report() -> dict:
    """The resolution report — every connection, every value, its winning tier
    and source, secrets masked. Local only: no network, no login attempt."""
    reg, reg_file = _connections_registry()
    report: dict = {"default": None, "connections": {}}
    if reg is None:
        value, tier, source = _resolve_env_key("CLICKUP_API_TOKEN")
        report["default"] = "default"
        settings = _connection_settings(None, None)
        report["connections"]["default"] = {
            "allow_write": WRITE_DEFAULT,
            "keys": [_key_report("CLICKUP_API_TOKEN", True, True, value, tier, source)],
            "settings": settings}
        return report
    conns = reg["connections"]
    report["default"] = reg.get("default") or \
        (next(iter(conns)) if len(conns) == 1 else None)
    for cid, entry in conns.items():
        entry = entry if isinstance(entry, dict) else {}
        secret_env = entry.get("secret_env")
        if secret_env:
            value, tier, source = _resolve_env_key(secret_env)
            keys = [_key_report(secret_env, True, True, value, tier, source)]
        else:
            keys = [_key_report("secret_env", False, True, None, None, None)]
        report["connections"][cid] = {
            "allow_write": bool(entry.get("allow_write", WRITE_DEFAULT)),
            "keys": keys,
            "settings": _connection_settings(entry, reg_file)}
    return report


def _cmd_connections() -> None:
    _emit(_connections_report())


# --- ClickUp-specific non-secret settings ------------------------------------

_UUID_RE = re.compile(
    r"^[0-9a-fA-F]{8}-[0-9a-fA-F]{4}-[0-9a-fA-F]{4}-[0-9a-fA-F]{4}-[0-9a-fA-F]{12}$"
)


def _resolve_setting(entry: dict | None, reg_file: Path | None,
                     entry_keys: tuple[str, ...], env_keys: tuple[str, ...]) \
        -> tuple[str | None, str | None, Path | None, str | None]:
    """Resolve a non-secret setting. Connection literals win, then env cascade."""
    if isinstance(entry, dict):
        for key in entry_keys:
            val = str(entry.get(key) or "").strip()
            if val:
                return val, "connection", reg_file, key
    for key in env_keys:
        val, tier, source = _resolve_env_key(key)
        if val:
            return val.strip(), tier, source, key
    return None, None, None, None


def _connection_settings(entry: dict | None, reg_file: Path | None) -> dict:
    field, field_tier, field_source, field_key = _resolve_setting(
        entry, reg_file,
        ("external_id_field", "external_id_field_id", "external_id"),
        ("CLICKUP_EXTERNAL_ID_FIELD", "CLICKUP_EXTERNAL_ID_FIELD_ID",
         "CLICKUP_EXTERNAL_ID"),
    )
    workspace, ws_tier, ws_source, ws_key = _resolve_setting(
        entry, reg_file,
        ("workspace_id", "workspace", "team_id"),
        ("CLICKUP_WORKSPACE_ID", "CLICKUP_TEAM_ID"),
    )
    return {
        "external_id_field": {"value": field, "tier": field_tier,
                              "source": str(field_source) if field_source else None,
                              "key": field_key},
        "workspace_id": {"value": workspace, "tier": ws_tier,
                         "source": str(ws_source) if ws_source else None,
                         "key": ws_key},
    }


# --- Reference parsing -------------------------------------------------------

def _ref(ref: str) -> str:
    """Accept a bare ClickUp task id or a full ClickUp URL; return the task id.
    ClickUp ids are opaque alphanumerics, so anything that is not clearly a URL
    is returned as-is."""
    ref = ref.strip()
    m = re.search(r"/t/(?:[A-Za-z0-9_-]+/)?([A-Za-z0-9_-]+)", ref)
    if m:
        return m.group(1)
    return ref


# --- Dates -------------------------------------------------------------------

def _epoch_ms_date(date: str) -> int:
    """YYYY-MM-DD → epoch milliseconds at UTC midnight (an all-day due date)."""
    try:
        dt = datetime.strptime(date, "%Y-%m-%d").replace(tzinfo=timezone.utc)
    except ValueError:
        _die(6, "bad_date", f"--due-on expects YYYY-MM-DD, got {date!r}")
    return int(dt.timestamp() * 1000)


def _epoch_ms_iso(iso: str) -> int:
    """ISO8601 → epoch milliseconds. Accepts a trailing Z."""
    raw = iso.strip().replace("Z", "+00:00")
    try:
        dt = datetime.fromisoformat(raw)
    except ValueError:
        _die(6, "bad_datetime", f"--due-at expects ISO8601, got {iso!r}",
             "e.g. 2026-06-30T16:00:00Z")
    if dt.tzinfo is None:
        dt = dt.replace(tzinfo=timezone.utc)
    return int(dt.timestamp() * 1000)


def _ts(epoch_ms) -> str:
    """ClickUp epoch-ms string/int → compact minute-precision UTC: 2026-06-10 14:40Z."""
    if not epoch_ms:
        return "?"
    try:
        dt = datetime.fromtimestamp(int(epoch_ms) / 1000, tz=timezone.utc)
    except (ValueError, TypeError, OSError):
        return "?"
    return dt.strftime("%Y-%m-%d %H:%M") + "Z"


# --- HTTP --------------------------------------------------------------------

def _client(token: str) -> httpx.Client:
    return httpx.Client(
        base_url=API_BASE,
        timeout=TIMEOUT,
        headers={
            "Authorization": token,   # personal pk_ token: raw, no scheme prefix
            "Accept": "application/json",
            "Content-Type": "application/json",
        },
    )


def _request(client: httpx.Client, method: str, path: str,
             params: dict | None = None, json_body: dict | None = None,
             allow_404: bool = False) -> dict | None:
    last_status: int | None = None
    for attempt in range(1, MAX_RETRIES + 1):
        try:
            resp = client.request(method, path, params=params, json=json_body)
        except httpx.TimeoutException:
            if attempt < MAX_RETRIES:
                time.sleep(attempt * 1.5)
                continue
            _die(5, "timeout", f"request timed out: {method} {path}",
                 "ClickUp API was unresponsive; check status.clickup.com")
        except httpx.RequestError as e:
            _die(5, "network_error", f"network error: {e}", "check connectivity")

        last_status = resp.status_code
        if resp.status_code == 429:
            # ClickUp carries no Retry-After; X-RateLimit-Reset is a Unix-seconds
            # timestamp to wait until. Fall back to the linear backoff.
            reset = resp.headers.get("X-RateLimit-Reset")
            wait = attempt * 1.5
            if reset:
                try:
                    wait = max(float(reset) - time.time(), 1.0)
                except ValueError:
                    pass
            if attempt < MAX_RETRIES:
                time.sleep(min(wait, 60.0))
                continue
            _die(5, "rate_limited", f"rate-limited after {MAX_RETRIES} attempts",
                 "back off and retry later", status=429)
        if resp.status_code >= 500:
            if attempt < MAX_RETRIES:
                time.sleep(attempt * 1.5)
                continue
            _die(5, "server_error", f"ClickUp returned {resp.status_code}",
                 "check status.clickup.com", status=resp.status_code)

        if resp.status_code == 204 or not resp.content:
            return {} if resp.status_code < 400 else None
        try:
            data = resp.json()
        except ValueError:
            if resp.status_code < 400:
                return {}
            _die(5, "invalid_response", f"non-JSON response from {method} {path}",
                 status=resp.status_code)

        if resp.status_code >= 400:
            if allow_404 and resp.status_code == 404:
                return None
            msg = (data.get("err") or data.get("error")
                   or data.get("message") or "unknown error") if isinstance(data, dict) else "error"
            ecode = data.get("ECODE") if isinstance(data, dict) else None
            if resp.status_code in (401, 403):
                _die(2, "unauthorized", msg,
                     "token may be invalid or lack access to this resource",
                     status=resp.status_code)
            if resp.status_code == 404:
                _die(3, "not_found", msg,
                     ecode or "verify the id and that the token can see it",
                     status=resp.status_code)
            if resp.status_code in (400, 402, 422):
                _die(6, "invalid_request", msg, ecode, status=resp.status_code)
            _die(5, "api_error", msg, ecode, status=resp.status_code)

        return data

    _die(5, "exhausted_retries", f"exhausted {MAX_RETRIES} attempts on {method} {path}",
         status=last_status)


# --- Input -------------------------------------------------------------------

def _read_text(src: str | None) -> str:
    if src is None or src == "-":
        return sys.stdin.read()
    if "\n" not in src:
        try:
            p = Path(src)
            if p.exists():
                return p.read_text()
        except OSError:
            pass
    return src


# --- Body helpers ------------------------------------------------------------

def _body_field(text: str | None, mode: str) -> dict:
    """A task body: markdown (default) → `markdown_content` (ClickUp renders it),
    plain → literal `description`."""
    if text is None:
        return {}
    return {"description": text} if mode == "plain" else {"markdown_content": text}


def _ids(values) -> list[int]:
    """Coerce user-id arguments to ints (ClickUp assignee/watcher ids are numeric)."""
    out = []
    for v in values:
        try:
            out.append(int(v))
        except (TypeError, ValueError):
            _die(6, "bad_user_id", f"expected a numeric user id, got {v!r}")
    return out


def _parse_fields(pairs: list[str]) -> list[dict]:
    """`UUID=VALUE` pairs → the create body's custom_fields (key `id`, not
    `field_id` — the create endpoint differs from the filter endpoint)."""
    out = []
    for p in pairs:
        if "=" not in p:
            _die(6, "bad_field", f"--field expects UUID=VALUE, got {p!r}")
        uuid, val = p.split("=", 1)
        out.append({"id": uuid.strip(), "value": val})
    return out


# --- Commands: identity & hierarchy ------------------------------------------

def cmd_whoami(c: httpx.Client) -> dict:
    return _request(c, "GET", "/user")["user"]


def cmd_workspaces(c: httpx.Client) -> list:
    return _request(c, "GET", "/team")["teams"]


def _sole_workspace(c: httpx.Client) -> str:
    teams = cmd_workspaces(c)
    if not teams:
        _die(3, "no_workspace", "the token sees no workspace")
    if len(teams) > 1:
        _die(6, "ambiguous_workspace",
             "the token sees several workspaces; pass --workspace <id>",
             "known: " + ", ".join(f"{t['id']} ({t.get('name')})" for t in teams))
    return teams[0]["id"]


def cmd_members(c: httpx.Client, workspace: str | None) -> list:
    teams = cmd_workspaces(c)
    if workspace:
        teams = [t for t in teams if str(t.get("id")) == str(workspace)]
        if not teams:
            _die(3, "not_found", f"no workspace {workspace!r} the token can see")
    elif len(teams) != 1:
        _die(6, "ambiguous_workspace",
             "several workspaces; pass --workspace <id>",
             "known: " + ", ".join(f"{t['id']} ({t.get('name')})" for t in teams))
    return [m.get("user", m) for m in (teams[0].get("members") or [])]


def cmd_spaces(c: httpx.Client, workspace: str) -> list:
    return _request(c, "GET", f"/team/{workspace}/space",
                    params={"archived": "false"})["spaces"]


def cmd_folders(c: httpx.Client, space: str) -> list:
    return _request(c, "GET", f"/space/{space}/folder",
                    params={"archived": "false"})["folders"]


def cmd_lists(c: httpx.Client, folder: str | None, space: str | None) -> list:
    if folder:
        return _request(c, "GET", f"/folder/{folder}/list",
                        params={"archived": "false"})["lists"]
    if space:
        return _request(c, "GET", f"/space/{space}/list",
                        params={"archived": "false"})["lists"]
    _die(6, "missing_parent", "lists requires --folder or --space",
         "--folder lists a folder's lists; --space lists the folderless lists")


def cmd_statuses(c: httpx.Client, list_id: str) -> list:
    lst = _request(c, "GET", f"/list/{list_id}")
    return lst.get("statuses") or []


def cmd_tags(c: httpx.Client, space: str) -> list:
    return _request(c, "GET", f"/space/{space}/tag")["tags"]


def cmd_fields(c: httpx.Client, list_id: str) -> list:
    return _request(c, "GET", f"/list/{list_id}/field")["fields"]


def _resolve_custom_field(c: httpx.Client, field: str | None,
                          list_id: str | None = None,
                          purpose: str = "custom field") -> str:
    """Accept a custom field UUID, or a field name when a list is available."""
    field = (field or "").strip()
    if not field:
        _die(6, "missing_field", f"no {purpose} configured",
             "set connection external_id_field or CLICKUP_EXTERNAL_ID_FIELD, "
             "or pass --field")
    if _UUID_RE.match(field):
        return field
    if not list_id:
        _die(6, "field_name_needs_list",
             f"{purpose} {field!r} is a name, not a UUID",
             "configure the field UUID, or pass --list where this command supports it")
    matches = [f for f in cmd_fields(c, list_id)
               if str(f.get("name") or "").lower() == field.lower()]
    if not matches:
        _die(3, "field_not_found",
             f"no custom field named {field!r} on list {list_id}",
             f"`clickup fields --list {list_id}` shows available fields")
    if len(matches) > 1:
        _die(6, "ambiguous_field",
             f"several custom fields named {field!r} on list {list_id}",
             "configure the field UUID instead of the name")
    return str(matches[0].get("id"))


# --- Commands: task reads ----------------------------------------------------

def cmd_tasks(c: httpx.Client, list_id: str, show_all: bool, archived: bool,
              subtasks: bool, statuses: list[str], limit: int,
              page: int | None) -> list:
    base: dict = {
        "include_closed": "true" if show_all else "false",
        "archived": "true" if archived else "false",
    }
    if subtasks:
        base["subtasks"] = "true"
    if statuses:
        base["statuses[]"] = statuses
    if page is not None:
        base["page"] = page
        return _request(c, "GET", f"/list/{list_id}/task", params=base)["tasks"]
    # Paginate (0-indexed) until last_page, a short page, or the limit is reached.
    out: list = []
    pg = 0
    while True:
        params = dict(base, page=pg)
        body = _request(c, "GET", f"/list/{list_id}/task", params=params)
        batch = body.get("tasks") or []
        out += batch
        if body.get("last_page") or len(batch) < 100 or len(out) >= limit:
            break
        pg += 1
    return out[:limit]


def cmd_task(c: httpx.Client, task: str, with_subtasks: bool = False,
             custom_id: bool = False, workspace: str | None = None) -> dict:
    params: dict = {"include_markdown_description": "true"}
    if with_subtasks:
        params["include_subtasks"] = "true"
    if custom_id:
        if not workspace:
            _die(6, "missing_workspace", "--custom-id requires --workspace <id>",
                 "ClickUp resolves a Custom Task ID only within a workspace")
        params["custom_task_ids"] = "true"
        params["team_id"] = workspace
        return _request(c, "GET", f"/task/{task}", params=params)
    return _request(c, "GET", f"/task/{_ref(task)}", params=params)


def cmd_comments(c: httpx.Client, task: str, limit: int) -> list:
    """The N most recent comments, in chronological order.

    ClickUp serves comments newest-first, 25 per page, paged backward by the
    last item's date + id. Walk back until we have `limit` (or run dry), then
    reverse to chronological order."""
    tid = _ref(task)
    collected: list = []
    start: str | None = None
    start_id: str | None = None
    while True:
        params: dict = {}
        if start is not None:
            params["start"] = start
            params["start_id"] = start_id
        page = _request(c, "GET", f"/task/{tid}/comment", params=params)
        batch = page.get("comments") or []
        if not batch:
            break
        collected += batch
        if len(collected) >= limit or len(batch) < 25:
            break
        last = batch[-1]
        start, start_id = last.get("date"), last.get("id")
    collected = collected[:limit]
    return list(reversed(collected))


def cmd_subtasks(c: httpx.Client, task: str) -> list:
    obj = cmd_task(c, task, with_subtasks=True)
    return obj.get("subtasks") or []


def _split_deps(task_obj: dict) -> tuple[list, list]:
    """From a task's dependencies[], split into (blockers, dependents):
    an entry links task_id → depends_on (task_id waits on depends_on)."""
    tid = task_obj.get("id")
    deps = task_obj.get("dependencies") or []
    blockers = [d["depends_on"] for d in deps
                if d.get("task_id") == tid and d.get("depends_on")]
    dependents = [d["task_id"] for d in deps
                  if d.get("depends_on") == tid and d.get("task_id")]
    return blockers, dependents


def cmd_deps(c: httpx.Client, task: str, dependents: bool) -> dict:
    obj = cmd_task(c, task)
    blockers, deps_of = _split_deps(obj)
    ids = deps_of if dependents else blockers
    return {"task": obj.get("id"),
            "relation": "dependents" if dependents else "dependencies",
            "task_ids": ids,
            "linked_tasks": obj.get("linked_tasks") or []}


def cmd_attachments(c: httpx.Client, task: str) -> list:
    obj = cmd_task(c, task)
    return obj.get("attachments") or []


def cmd_find(c: httpx.Client, workspace: str, custom_task_id: str | None = None,
             field: str | None = None, value: str | None = None) -> dict | None:
    """Resolve a task by a dedup key, returning the task or None on a miss.

    Two modes — the external-ID parity path is the custom-field one, because
    ClickUp Custom Task IDs cannot be set via the API:
      --field <uuid> --value <v>  → the first task whose custom field equals <v>
                                     (workspace-wide; the settable dedup key).
      <custom-task-id>            → the ClickApp Custom Task ID point lookup.
    A dedup-key field is meant to be unique; only the first match is returned."""
    if field is not None:
        flt = json.dumps([{"field_id": field, "operator": "=", "value": value}])
        body = _request(c, "GET", f"/team/{workspace}/task",
                        params={"custom_fields": flt})
        tasks = (body or {}).get("tasks") or []
        return tasks[0] if tasks else None
    res = _request(c, "GET", f"/task/{custom_task_id}",
                   params={"custom_task_ids": "true", "team_id": workspace},
                   allow_404=True)
    return res or None


def _idle(now_ms: int, updated) -> str:
    """Human idle age since the last touch (date_updated, epoch-ms)."""
    if not updated:
        return "?"
    try:
        secs = max((now_ms - int(updated)) / 1000, 0)
    except (ValueError, TypeError):
        return "?"
    d, h, m = int(secs // 86400), int((secs % 86400) // 3600), int((secs % 3600) // 60)
    if d:
        return f"{d}d{h}h"
    if h:
        return f"{h}h{m}m"
    return f"{m}m"


def cmd_assigned(c: httpx.Client, workspace: str, assignee: str | None,
                 show_all: bool, statuses: list[str], limit: int) -> list:
    """Tasks assigned to a user (default: the token's own identity), incomplete
    unless show_all, stalest-first, each annotated with its last-touch timestamp
    and idle age — the 'what is waiting on my input, and for how long?' read."""
    if not assignee:
        assignee = str(cmd_whoami(c).get("id"))
    base: dict = {"assignees[]": [assignee],
                  "include_closed": "true" if show_all else "false"}
    if statuses:
        base["statuses[]"] = statuses
    out: list = []
    pg = 0
    while True:
        body = _request(c, "GET", f"/team/{workspace}/task", params=dict(base, page=pg))
        batch = body.get("tasks") or []
        out += batch
        # The team-tasks endpoint does not reliably return `last_page`; a short
        # (<100) or empty page is the dependable end-of-pages signal.
        if body.get("last_page") or len(batch) < 100 or len(out) >= limit:
            break
        pg += 1
    out = out[:limit]
    out.sort(key=lambda t: int(t.get("date_updated") or 0))   # stalest first
    now_ms = int(datetime.now(timezone.utc).timestamp() * 1000)
    return [{"id": t.get("id"), "name": t.get("name"),
             "status": (t.get("status") or {}).get("status"),
             "list": (t.get("list") or {}).get("name"),
             "last_touch": _ts(t.get("date_updated")),
             "idle": _idle(now_ms, t.get("date_updated")),
             "url": t.get("url")} for t in out]


# --- task-context ------------------------------------------------------------

def cmd_task_context(c: httpx.Client, task: str, as_json: bool = False):
    """The task plus everything adjacent, in one call: description, comment
    thread, attachment pointers, dependencies one level deep (each with its own
    description, thread, attachments), dependents as state lines."""
    obj = cmd_task(c, task)
    tid = obj.get("id")
    obj["comments"] = cmd_comments(c, tid, 100)
    blockers, dependents = _split_deps(obj)
    deps_full = []
    for dep_id in blockers:
        detail = cmd_task(c, dep_id)
        detail["comments"] = cmd_comments(c, dep_id, 100)
        deps_full.append(detail)
    obj["_dependencies_full"] = deps_full
    obj["_dependent_ids"] = dependents
    assembled = datetime.now(timezone.utc).strftime("%Y-%m-%dT%H:%M:%SZ")
    if as_json:
        return {"assembled_at": assembled, "task": obj}
    return _render_task_context(obj, assembled)


def _status_label(o: dict) -> str:
    st = o.get("status") or {}
    if isinstance(st, dict):
        return (st.get("status") or "?").upper()
    return str(st).upper()


def _render_task_context(t: dict, assembled: str) -> str:
    def comment_block(comments: list, h: str) -> list[str]:
        lines = [f"{h} Comments ({len(comments)})"]
        for s in comments:
            body = (s.get("comment_text") or "").strip() or "(no text — see attachments)"
            who = (s.get("user") or {}).get("username", "?")
            lines += ["", f"[{_ts(s.get('date'))} · {who}] {body}"]
        return lines

    def attachment_block(atts: list, h: str) -> list[str]:
        lines = [f"{h} Attachments ({len(atts)})"]
        lines += [f"{a.get('id')} · {a.get('title', '?')} · {a.get('url', '')}"
                  for a in atts]
        return lines

    out = [f"# Task {t.get('id')} — {t.get('name', '')}"]
    loc = " / ".join(filter(None, [
        (t.get("space") or {}).get("name") if isinstance(t.get("space"), dict) else None,
        (t.get("folder") or {}).get("name") if isinstance(t.get("folder"), dict) else None,
        (t.get("list") or {}).get("name") if isinstance(t.get("list"), dict) else None,
    ]))
    out.append(f"{loc + ' · ' if loc else ''}Status: {_status_label(t)}")
    assignees = ", ".join(a.get("username", "?") for a in (t.get("assignees") or [])) or "—"
    meta = (f"Assignees: {assignees}"
            f" · Created: {_ts(t.get('date_created'))}"
            f" · Updated: {_ts(t.get('date_updated'))}")
    due = t.get("due_date")
    if due:
        meta += f" · Due: {_ts(due)}"
    out.append(meta)
    out.append(f"Assembled: {assembled} (UTC) — tracker snapshot at pickup; "
               "live state may have moved since")
    body = (t.get("markdown_description") or t.get("description") or "").strip()
    out += ["", "## Description", body or "(empty)"]
    out += [""] + comment_block(t.get("comments", []), "##")
    out += [""] + attachment_block(t.get("attachments") or [], "##")
    for d in t.get("_dependencies_full", []):
        out += ["", f"## Dependency {d.get('id')} — {d.get('name', '')}",
                f"Status: {_status_label(d)} · Assignees: "
                + (", ".join(a.get("username", "?") for a in (d.get("assignees") or [])) or "—"),
                "", "### Description",
                (d.get("markdown_description") or d.get("description") or "").strip() or "(empty)"]
        out += [""] + comment_block(d.get("comments", []), "###")
    dependents = t.get("_dependent_ids", [])
    if dependents:
        out += ["", f"## Dependents ({len(dependents)})"]
        out += [f"- {x}" for x in dependents]
    return "\n".join(out) + "\n"


# --- Commands: task writes ---------------------------------------------------

def cmd_create(c: httpx.Client, list_id: str, name: str, body: str | None,
               body_mode: str, assignees: list[str], status: str | None,
               tags: list[str], priority: int | None, due_on: str | None,
               due_at: str | None, parent: str | None,
               custom_fields: list[dict] | None = None,
               workspace: str | None = None, external_id: str | None = None,
               external_id_field: str | None = None) -> dict:
    if due_on and due_at:
        _die(6, "conflicting_due", "pass only one of --due-on / --due-at",
             "--due-at carries the time-of-day; --due-on is all-day")
    if external_id is not None:
        external_id = str(external_id).strip()
        if not external_id:
            _die(6, "empty_external_id", "--external-id cannot be empty")
        if not workspace:
            _die(6, "missing_workspace",
                 "--external-id dedup requires --workspace or configured workspace_id",
                 "set connection workspace_id or CLICKUP_WORKSPACE_ID")
        external_id_field = _resolve_custom_field(
            c, external_id_field, list_id, purpose="external-id field")
        existing = cmd_find(c, workspace, field=external_id_field, value=external_id)
        if existing:
            return {"deduped": True, "external_id": external_id,
                    "external_id_field": external_id_field, "task": existing}
        custom_fields = list(custom_fields or [])
        custom_fields = [f for f in custom_fields
                         if str(f.get("id")) != str(external_id_field)]
        custom_fields.append({"id": external_id_field, "value": external_id})
    data: dict = {"name": name}
    data.update(_body_field(body, body_mode))
    if assignees:
        data["assignees"] = _ids(assignees)
    if status:
        data["status"] = status
    if tags:
        data["tags"] = tags
    if priority is not None:
        data["priority"] = priority
    if due_on:
        data["due_date"] = _epoch_ms_date(due_on)
        data["due_date_time"] = False
    if due_at:
        data["due_date"] = _epoch_ms_iso(due_at)
        data["due_date_time"] = True
    if parent:
        data["parent"] = _ref(parent)
    if custom_fields:
        data["custom_fields"] = custom_fields
    created = _request(c, "POST", f"/list/{list_id}/task", json_body=data)
    if external_id is not None:
        return {"deduped": False, "external_id": external_id,
                "external_id_field": external_id_field, "task": created}
    return created


def cmd_update(c: httpx.Client, task: str, name: str | None, body: str | None,
               body_mode: str, status: str | None, priority: int | None,
               due_on: str | None, due_at: str | None,
               add_assignees: list[str], rem_assignees: list[str],
               archive: bool) -> dict:
    if due_on and due_at:
        _die(6, "conflicting_due", "pass only one of --due-on / --due-at",
             "--due-at carries the time-of-day; --due-on is all-day")
    data: dict = {}
    if name is not None:
        data["name"] = name
    data.update(_body_field(body, body_mode))
    if status:
        data["status"] = status
    if priority is not None:
        data["priority"] = priority
    if due_on:
        data["due_date"] = _epoch_ms_date(due_on)
        data["due_date_time"] = False
    if due_at:
        data["due_date"] = _epoch_ms_iso(due_at)
        data["due_date_time"] = True
    if add_assignees or rem_assignees:
        data["assignees"] = {"add": _ids(add_assignees), "rem": _ids(rem_assignees)}
    if archive:
        data["archived"] = True
    if not data:
        _die(6, "no_changes", "update requires at least one field to change",
             "pass --name / --desc / --markdown / --status / --priority / "
             "--due-on / --due-at / --add-assignee / --rem-assignee / --archive")
    return _request(c, "PUT", f"/task/{_ref(task)}", json_body=data)


def cmd_comment(c: httpx.Client, task: str, text: str,
                assignee: str | None, notify_all: bool) -> dict:
    data: dict = {"comment_text": text, "notify_all": notify_all}
    if assignee:
        data["assignee"] = int(assignee) if str(assignee).isdigit() else assignee
    return _request(c, "POST", f"/task/{_ref(task)}/comment", json_body=data)


def cmd_assign(c: httpx.Client, task: str, add: list[str], rem: list[str]) -> dict:
    if not add and not rem:
        _die(6, "no_assignees", "assign requires --add and/or --rem")
    return _request(c, "PUT", f"/task/{_ref(task)}",
                    json_body={"assignees": {"add": _ids(add), "rem": _ids(rem)}})


def cmd_watch(c: httpx.Client, task: str, add: list[str], rem: list[str]) -> dict:
    if not add and not rem:
        _die(6, "no_watchers", "watch requires --add and/or --rem")
    return _request(c, "PUT", f"/task/{_ref(task)}",
                    json_body={"watchers": {"add": _ids(add), "rem": _ids(rem)}})


def cmd_tag_create(c: httpx.Client, space: str, name: str,
                   fg: str | None, bg: str | None) -> dict:
    tag: dict = {"name": name}
    if fg:
        tag["tag_fg"] = fg
    if bg:
        tag["tag_bg"] = bg
    _request(c, "POST", f"/space/{space}/tag", json_body={"tag": tag})
    return {"space": space, "tag": name, "created": True}


def cmd_tag_add(c: httpx.Client, task: str, tag: str) -> dict:
    _request(c, "POST", f"/task/{_ref(task)}/tag/{tag}")
    return {"task": _ref(task), "tag": tag, "added": True}


def cmd_tag_remove(c: httpx.Client, task: str, tag: str) -> dict:
    _request(c, "DELETE", f"/task/{_ref(task)}/tag/{tag}")
    return {"task": _ref(task), "tag": tag, "removed": True}


def cmd_dep_add(c: httpx.Client, task: str, on: list[str]) -> dict:
    tid = _ref(task)
    for dep in on:
        _request(c, "POST", f"/task/{tid}/dependency",
                 json_body={"depends_on": _ref(dep)})
    return {"task": tid, "depends_on": [_ref(d) for d in on]}


def cmd_dep_remove(c: httpx.Client, task: str, on: list[str]) -> dict:
    tid = _ref(task)
    for dep in on:
        _request(c, "DELETE", f"/task/{tid}/dependency",
                 params={"depends_on": _ref(dep)})
    return {"task": tid, "removed": [_ref(d) for d in on]}


def cmd_field_set(c: httpx.Client, task: str, field: str,
                  value, as_json: bool) -> dict:
    if as_json:
        try:
            value = json.loads(value)
        except (ValueError, TypeError):
            _die(6, "bad_json", "--value is not valid JSON (omit --json for a literal)")
    _request(c, "POST", f"/task/{_ref(task)}/field/{field}",
             json_body={"value": value})
    return {"task": _ref(task), "field": field, "set": True}


def cmd_field_clear(c: httpx.Client, task: str, field: str) -> dict:
    _request(c, "DELETE", f"/task/{_ref(task)}/field/{field}")
    return {"task": _ref(task), "field": field, "cleared": True}


def cmd_field_get(c: httpx.Client, task: str, field: str | None):
    """Read a task's custom field values (the full definition + per-task value),
    all of them or one addressed by UUID or name."""
    fields = cmd_task(c, task).get("custom_fields") or []
    rows = [{"id": f.get("id"), "name": f.get("name"), "type": f.get("type"),
             "value": f.get("value")} for f in fields]
    if field:
        for r in rows:
            if r["id"] == field or r["name"] == field:
                return r
        _die(3, "not_found", f"no custom field {field!r} on this task",
             "`clickup fields --list <id>` lists the field definitions")
    return rows


def cmd_task_delete(c: httpx.Client, task: str, custom_id: bool,
                    workspace: str | None) -> dict:
    if custom_id:
        if not workspace:
            _die(6, "missing_workspace", "--custom-id requires --workspace <id>")
        tid, params = task, {"custom_task_ids": "true", "team_id": workspace}
    else:
        tid, params = _ref(task), None
    _request(c, "DELETE", f"/task/{tid}", params=params)
    return {"task": tid, "deleted": True}


def cmd_list_create(c: httpx.Client, folder: str | None, space: str | None,
                    name: str, content: str | None) -> dict:
    data: dict = {"name": name}
    if content:
        data["content"] = content
    if folder:
        return _request(c, "POST", f"/folder/{folder}/list", json_body=data)
    if space:
        return _request(c, "POST", f"/space/{space}/list", json_body=data)
    _die(6, "missing_parent", "list-create requires --folder or --space")


# --- Completion (status-based, with dependency gate + roll-up) ---------------

_DONE_TYPES = ("done", "closed")


def _is_done(task_obj: dict) -> bool:
    st = task_obj.get("status") or {}
    return isinstance(st, dict) and st.get("type") in _DONE_TYPES


def _list_id_of(task_obj: dict) -> str | None:
    lst = task_obj.get("list")
    return lst.get("id") if isinstance(lst, dict) else None


def _status_of_type(c: httpx.Client, list_id: str, types: tuple) -> str | None:
    """The label of this list's first status whose type is in `types`."""
    for st in cmd_statuses(c, list_id):
        if st.get("type") in types:
            return st.get("status")
    return None


def _incomplete_blockers(c: httpx.Client, task_obj: dict) -> list:
    """Blocker task ids of task_obj that are not yet in a done/closed status."""
    blockers, _ = _split_deps(task_obj)
    out = []
    for bid in blockers:
        try:
            bt = cmd_task(c, bid)
        except SystemExit:
            raise
        if not _is_done(bt):
            out.append({"id": bid, "name": bt.get("name"),
                        "status": _status_label(bt)})
    return out


def _rollup_parents(c: httpx.Client, task_obj: dict) -> list:
    """Walk up from a just-completed task; complete each parent whose subtasks
    are ALL done. Returns the parents auto-completed."""
    rolled: list = []
    parent_id = task_obj.get("parent")
    while parent_id:
        parent = cmd_task(c, parent_id, with_subtasks=True)
        subs = parent.get("subtasks") or []
        if not subs or not all(_is_done(s) for s in subs):
            break
        plist = _list_id_of(parent)
        done = _status_of_type(c, plist, _DONE_TYPES) if plist else None
        if not done:
            break
        _request(c, "PUT", f"/task/{parent.get('id')}", json_body={"status": done})
        rolled.append({"id": parent.get("id"), "name": parent.get("name")})
        parent_id = parent.get("parent")
    return rolled


def _newly_unblocked(c: httpx.Client, task_obj: dict) -> list:
    """Tasks that depended on this one and are now fully unblocked."""
    _, dependents = _split_deps(task_obj)
    out = []
    for did in dependents:
        dt = cmd_task(c, did)
        if not _incomplete_blockers(c, dt):
            out.append({"id": did, "name": dt.get("name")})
    return out


def cmd_complete(c: httpx.Client, task: str, reopen: bool,
                 force: bool, no_rollup: bool) -> dict:
    obj = cmd_task(c, task)
    tid = obj.get("id")
    list_id = _list_id_of(obj)
    if not list_id:
        _die(6, "no_list", f"task {tid} has no resolvable list to read statuses from")

    if reopen:
        target = _status_of_type(c, list_id, ("open",))
        if not target:
            _die(6, "no_open_status", "this task's list has no 'open' status to reopen into")
        updated = _request(c, "PUT", f"/task/{tid}", json_body={"status": target})
        return {"reopened": {"id": tid, "status": target}, "task": updated}

    blockers = _incomplete_blockers(c, obj)
    if blockers and not force:
        names = ", ".join(f"{b.get('name','?')} ({b['id']})" for b in blockers)
        _die(7, "blocked_by_dependencies",
             f"{len(blockers)} incomplete dependenc{'y' if len(blockers)==1 else 'ies'}: {names}",
             "resolve them first, or pass --force to complete anyway")

    target = _status_of_type(c, list_id, _DONE_TYPES)
    if not target:
        _die(6, "no_done_status",
             "this task's list has no 'done' or 'closed' status to complete into",
             f"`clickup statuses --list {list_id}` shows the available columns")
    completed = _request(c, "PUT", f"/task/{tid}", json_body={"status": target})

    result: dict = {"completed": {"id": tid, "status": target}, "task": completed}
    if not no_rollup:
        rolled = _rollup_parents(c, obj)
        unblocked = _newly_unblocked(c, obj)
        if rolled:
            result["rolled_up"] = rolled
        if unblocked:
            result["unblocked"] = unblocked
    return result


# --- Deliverable (paired human-request + dependent task) ---------------------

def cmd_deliverable(c: httpx.Client, *, list_id: str, request_name: str,
                    request_body: str | None, agent_name: str,
                    agent_body: str | None, supervisor: str, agent: str,
                    status: str | None = None, parent: str | None = None,
                    state_field: str | None = None) -> dict:
    """Create a paired request + dependent agent task. The request is assigned to
    --supervisor (the human whose input is needed); the agent task is assigned to
    --agent and DEPENDS ON the request, so completing the request unblocks it.
    Not idempotent — ClickUp exposes no settable dedup key, so a re-run makes a
    fresh pair."""
    req = cmd_create(c, list_id, request_name, request_body, "markdown",
                     [supervisor], status, [], None, None, None, None)
    ag = cmd_create(c, list_id, agent_name, agent_body, "markdown",
                    [agent], status, [], None, None, None, parent)
    cmd_dep_add(c, ag["id"], [req["id"]])
    out = {"request": {"id": req.get("id"), "name": req.get("name"), "url": req.get("url")},
           "agent": {"id": ag.get("id"), "name": ag.get("name"), "url": ag.get("url")},
           "dependency": {"dependent": ag.get("id"), "on": req.get("id")}}
    if state_field:
        now_ms = int(datetime.now(timezone.utc).timestamp() * 1000)
        state = json.dumps({"phase": "waiting", "last_touch": now_ms})
        cmd_field_set(c, req["id"], state_field, state, as_json=False)
        cmd_field_set(c, ag["id"], state_field, state, as_json=False)
        out["state_field"] = state_field
    return out


# --- Attachments (multipart upload) ------------------------------------------

def cmd_attach(token: str, task: str, file_path: str, name: str | None) -> dict:
    p = Path(file_path)
    if not p.exists() or not p.is_file():
        _die(6, "file_not_found", f"{file_path} is not a readable file",
             "pass a path to a local file (ClickUp has no attach-by-URL)")
    tid = _ref(task)
    headers = {"Authorization": token, "Accept": "application/json"}
    files = {"attachment": (name or p.name, p.read_bytes())}
    with httpx.Client(base_url=API_BASE, timeout=httpx.Timeout(120.0),
                      headers=headers) as c:
        for attempt in range(1, MAX_RETRIES + 1):
            try:
                resp = c.post(f"/task/{tid}/attachment", files=files)
            except httpx.TimeoutException:
                if attempt < MAX_RETRIES:
                    time.sleep(attempt * 1.5); continue
                _die(5, "timeout", f"upload timed out: POST /task/{tid}/attachment",
                     "ClickUp API was unresponsive; check status.clickup.com")
            except httpx.RequestError as e:
                _die(5, "network_error", f"network error: {e}", "check connectivity")
            if resp.status_code == 429 or resp.status_code >= 500:
                if attempt < MAX_RETRIES:
                    time.sleep(attempt * 1.5); continue
            try:
                body = resp.json()
            except ValueError:
                _die(5, "invalid_response",
                     f"non-JSON response from POST /task/{tid}/attachment",
                     status=resp.status_code)
            if resp.status_code >= 400:
                msg = body.get("err") or body.get("message") or "unknown error"
                if resp.status_code in (401, 403):
                    _die(2, "unauthorized", msg,
                         "token may be invalid or lack access", status=resp.status_code)
                if resp.status_code == 404:
                    _die(3, "not_found", msg,
                         "verify the task id and that the token can see it",
                         status=resp.status_code)
                _die(6, "invalid_request", msg, status=resp.status_code)
            return body
    _die(5, "exhausted_retries", f"exhausted {MAX_RETRIES} attempts on POST /task/{tid}/attachment")


# --- Webhooks ----------------------------------------------------------------

def cmd_webhooks(c: httpx.Client, workspace: str) -> list:
    return _request(c, "GET", f"/team/{workspace}/webhook")["webhooks"]


def cmd_webhook_create(c: httpx.Client, workspace: str, endpoint: str,
                       events: list[str], space: str | None, folder: str | None,
                       list_id: str | None, task: str | None) -> dict:
    data: dict = {"endpoint": endpoint, "events": events or "*"}
    if space:
        data["space_id"] = space
    if folder:
        data["folder_id"] = folder
    if list_id:
        data["list_id"] = list_id
    if task:
        data["task_id"] = _ref(task)
    return _request(c, "POST", f"/team/{workspace}/webhook", json_body=data)


def cmd_webhook_delete(c: httpx.Client, webhook: str) -> dict:
    _request(c, "DELETE", f"/webhook/{webhook}")
    return {"webhook": webhook, "deleted": True}


# --- doctor ------------------------------------------------------------------

def _check_connection(token: str) -> dict:
    """One connection's round-trip, reported rather than died — doctor covers
    every connection, so a broken one becomes a finding, not a stop."""
    try:
        with _client(token) as c:
            r = c.get("/user")
            if r.status_code >= 400:
                cat = 2 if r.status_code in (401, 403) else 5
                return {"ok": False, "category": cat,
                        "error": f"/user returned {r.status_code}"}
            user = r.json()["user"]
            tr = c.get("/team")
            teams = tr.json().get("teams", []) if tr.status_code < 400 else []
            return {"ok": True,
                    "whoami": user.get("username") or user.get("email"),
                    "workspaces": [t.get("name") for t in teams]}
    except httpx.RequestError as e:
        return {"ok": False, "category": 5, "error": f"network error: {e}"}
    except (ValueError, KeyError) as e:
        return {"ok": False, "category": 5, "error": f"bad response: {e}"}


def cmd_doctor(reg: dict | None, wanted: str | None,
               token_key_override: str | None) -> None:
    """Every connection bare; one with --connection. Exit 0 only when every
    examined connection is healthy, else the first failure's category."""
    _doctor_gate(_connections_report(), wanted)
    if wanted is not None or reg is None:
        targets = [_select_connection(reg, wanted)]
    else:
        targets = list(reg["connections"].items())
    connections: dict = {}
    fail_exit = 0
    for cid, entry in targets:
        key = token_key_override or \
            ("CLICKUP_API_TOKEN" if entry is None else entry.get("secret_env"))
        if not key:
            res = {"ok": False, "category": 6,
                   "error": f"connection {cid!r} is missing 'secret_env'"}
        else:
            token = _resolve_env_key(key)[0]
            if not token:
                res = {"ok": False, "category": 2,
                       "error": f"{key} not found in a project .env, "
                                f"{CREDENTIALS_ENV}, or the environment"}
            else:
                res = _check_connection(token)
        if not res.get("ok") and not fail_exit:
            fail_exit = res.get("category") or 5
        res.pop("category", None)
        connections[cid] = res
    _emit({"ok": fail_exit == 0, "connections": connections})
    if fail_exit:
        sys.exit(fail_exit)


